19 Io mi volsi dallato con paura
20 d’essere abbandonato, quand’ io vidi
21 solo dinanzi a me la terra oscura;

22 e ’l mio conforto: «Perché pur diffidi?»,
23 a dir mi cominciò tutto rivolto;
24 «non credi tu me teco e ch’io ti guidi?

25 Vespero è già colà dov’ è sepolto
26 lo corpo dentro al quale io facea ombra;
27 Napoli l’ha, e da Brandizio è tolto.

query.result:
19 I turned to the side in fear 20 of being abandoned, when I saw 21 only the dark earth in front of me;
22 and my comfort, turning completely towards me, 23 began to say to me: "Why do you still doubt? 24 Do you not believe that I am with you and that I am guiding you?
25 Evening is already there where the body 26 within which I cast a shadow is buried; 27 Naples has it, and it was taken from Brindisi.

37 Be content, human race, with the quia; 38 for if you could have seen everything, 39 it would not have been necessary for Mary to give birth;
40 and you saw in vain the desire 41 of those whose desire would have been appeased, 42 which is eternally given to them as mourning:
43 I speak of Aristotle and Plato 44 and many others"; and here he bowed his head, 45 and said no more, and remained troubled.

46 Meanwhile we reached the foot of the mountain;
47 there we found the rock so steep,
48 that swift legs would have been in vain.

64 Then he looked, and with a free expression
65 he replied: "Let us go over there, for they are coming slowly;
66 and you, my sweet son, keep your hope firm".

